Activity 6: Bubble Painting

Age Group: 2–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s): Sensory exploration, painting, creativity, color exploration, fine motor skills.

Materials: Bubble solution, washable paint or food coloring, small cups, drinking straws (or bubble wands), white cardstock or watercolor paper, paper towels.

Instructions: Pour bubble solution into small cups and add washable paint. Blow gently through the straw to make bubbles. Place paper over the bubbles to create
colorful prints. Repeat with different colors and let dry.

What We'll Learn: Explore color mixing, strengthen fine motor skills, practice controlled breathing, and encourage creativity.

ADApt: Children who cannot blow through a straw can use bubble wands while an adult creates the bubbles. Older children can experiment with layered colors.

Monserrat's Tip: Turn your bubble prints into a magical garden by drawing flowers or butterflies after they dry.

Safety Notes: Use only non-toxic materials. Adult supervision is recommended. Remind children to blow, not suck, through the straw.

Video Script: (To be completed by Lilian.)

Reference / Inspiration: Air Child Care Training Solutions – Bubble Painting.
