Activity 8: Finger Painting Fun

Age Group:
2–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s):
Creative Art, Sensory Play, Fine Motor Skills, Color Exploration

Materials:
Washable finger paints, thick white paper, apron or old shirt, baby wipes or damp cloth, newspaper or table cover.

Instructions:
Cover your work area before you begin. Pour small amounts of washable finger paint onto a tray or paper plate. Invite children to explore the paint using their fingers, hands, 
or even the side of their hand to make different shapes and patterns. Encourage them to mix colors, create pictures, or simply enjoy the process of painting. Allow the artwork to dry 
completely before displaying it.

What We'll Learn
Explore colors by mixing them together.
Practice fine motor skills through hand movements.
Encourage creativity and self-expression.
Experience different textures through sensory play.
ADApt

Children who prefer not to touch paint can use paintbrushes, sponges, cotton balls, or silicone painting tools. For younger children, use fewer colors at first to avoid feeling overwhelmed. Older 
children can create pictures, tell a story about their artwork, or experiment with color mixing.

Monserrat's Tip
There isn't a "right" way to finger paint. Every picture is special because it shows your own imagination. When you're finished, hang your artwork somewhere at home and celebrate your creativity!

Safety Notes
Use only non-toxic, washable finger paints. Adult supervision is recommended, especially with younger children. Wash hands thoroughly after the activity.

Finger Painting Fun Video Script: (To be completed by Lilian.)

Reference / Inspiration

Primary Source: 
Crayola – Finger Painting Ideas
Additional Inspiration: NAEYC (National Association for the Education of Young Children) – Process Art resources
