Activity 9: Salt Painting

Age Group:
3–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s):
Creative Art, Sensory Play, Fine Motor Skills, Color Exploration

Materials:
White cardstock or thick paper, white school glue, table salt, liquid watercolors or diluted food coloring, paintbrush or eyedropper, tray or newspaper.

Instructions:
Draw a simple design on the paper using white glue. Sprinkle salt over the glue until it is completely covered, then gently shake off the extra salt. Using a paintbrush
or eyedropper, carefully add small drops of watercolor to the salt. Watch as the colors spread through the salt, creating beautiful patterns. Allow the artwork to dry completely before displaying it.

What We'll Learn:
Explore how liquids move through different materials. Practice fine motor skills while using glue and paint.
Discover how colors blend together.
Encourage patience while observing the painting develop.

ADApt:
For younger children, draw the glue design ahead of time so they can focus on adding the colors. Children with limited hand strength can use larger glue bottles or thicker paintbrushes.
If using an eyedropper is difficult, a small paintbrush works just as well.

Monserrat's Tip
Try drawing a rainbow, a star, your name, or your favorite animal. Every design looks different once the colors begin to spread!

