Activity 10: Ice Painting

Age Group:
2–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s):
Creative Art, Sensory Exploration, Science Discovery, Outdoor or Indoor Play

Materials:
Ice cube tray, water, washable paint or food coloring, popsicle sticks (optional), white paper or cardstock, tray or towel.

Instructions:
Freeze colored water in an ice cube tray. If you would like easy-to-hold painting tools, place a popsicle stick into each ice cube before freezing. Once frozen, place the colored ice cubes on a tray and invite children to paint by sliding them across the paper. Watch as the melting ice creates colorful designs. Let the artwork dry before displaying it.

What We'll Learn: 
Observe how ice changes as it melts. Explore colors in a new and exciting way. Strengthen hand coordination while painting. Encourage creativity through sensory exploration.

ADApt
Children who are sensitive to cold can wear lightweight gloves or hold the popsicle stick instead of the ice. Older children can experiment by layering colors or comparing which ice cubes melt the fastest.

Monserrat's Tip: 
Take your painting outside on a warm day and watch how the sunshine changes your artwork as the ice melts. It's like painting with nature!

Safety Notes:
Use only non-toxic coloring materials. Dry any wet floors immediately to prevent slipping. Adult supervision is recommended.

Ice Painting Video Script

(To be completed by Lilian.)

Reference / Inspiration

Primary Source: PBS Kids – Ice Painting Activities

Additional Inspiration: Raising Children Network – Sensory Play Ideas

