Activity 11: Spin Art

Age Group:
3–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s):
Creative Art, Color Exploration, Process Art, Fine Motor Skills

Materials:
White cardstock or thick paper cut into a circle (or small square), washable paint, salad spinner (or homemade spinning device), small spoons or squeeze bottles, paper towels, apron or old shirt.

Instructions:
Place the paper inside the salad spinner. Add a few drops of different paint colors to the center of the paper. Close the lid and spin the basket several times. Carefully open the spinner to reveal your colorful design. If you'd like, add a few more drops of paint and spin again to create new patterns. Let the artwork dry completely before displaying it.

What We'll Learn:
Discover how spinning changes the way paint moves, Explore color mixing through movement, Strengthen hand coordination while using the spinner.
Encourage creativity by experimenting with different color combinations.

ADApt

Children who have difficulty spinning the basket can work with a partner or ask an adult for help. Younger children may enjoy choosing the colors while an adult operates
the spinner. Older children can compare how slow and fast spinning creates different designs.

Monserrat's Tip:

Every spin creates a surprise! Try using only two colors first, then create another picture using three or four colors to see how the designs change.

Safety Notes

Adult supervision is recommended. Make sure the spinner is securely closed before spinning to avoid paint splatters. Use only washable, non-toxic paints.

Spin Art Video Script

(To be completed by Lilian.)

