Activity 12: Nature Texture Rubbings

Age Group:
3–12 years (focus changes according to age)

Category(s):
Creative Art, Nature Exploration, Fine Motor Skills

Materials:
Paper, crayons with the wrappers removed, leaves, tree bark, feathers, coins, textured objects, clipboard (optional).

Instructions:
Place a leaf or another textured object under a sheet of paper. Hold the paper still with one hand and gently rub the side of a crayon over the paper until the texture appears. 
Try different objects and colors to create a collection of texture prints. Compare the patterns and create a collage using your favorite rubbings.

What We'll Learn
Discover textures found in nature and everyday objects. Practice fine motor control while using crayons. Develop observation and comparison skills.
Encourage curiosity about the natural world. Build vocabulary by describing textures such as rough, smooth, bumpy, and soft.

ADApt
Secure the paper with masking tape if it moves easily. Larger leaves and textured objects may be easier for younger children to use. Children with visual impairments 
can explore each object by touch before making the rubbing. Offer thick crayons or adaptive grips if additional hand support is helpful.

Monserrat's Tip
Go on a little "texture hunt" around your home or yard. You might be surprised by all the beautiful patterns hiding in everyday things!

Safety Notes
Choose natural materials that are clean and safe to handle. Avoid plants that may cause skin irritation. Wash hands after collecting items outdoors.

Nature Texture Rubbings Video Script: 
(To be completed by Lilian.)

Reference / Inspiration

Primary Source: Crayola – Leaf and Texture Rubbings

