Activity 14: Tissue Paper Suncatcher

Age Group:
3–12 years

Category(s):
Creative Art, Color Exploration, Fine Motor Skills

Materials:
Contact paper, colorful tissue paper, child-safe scissors, construction paper (optional), tape.

Instructions:
Cut small pieces of colorful tissue paper. Place them onto the sticky side of contact paper to create any design you like. Cover with a second sheet of contact paper if desired. Hang your finished 
suncatcher in a sunny window and watch the light shine through the colors.

What We'll Learn: 
Explore color, light, and transparency. Strengthen fine motor skills through placing small pieces. Encourage creativity and design.
Observe how sunlight changes throughout the day.

ADApt
Use larger tissue paper pieces for younger children or anyone who benefits from easier handling. Children with limited hand strength can press the tissue paper using the palm of their hand instead of fingertips.

Monserrat's Tip
Try looking at your suncatcher in the morning and again in the afternoon. The sunlight can make the colors look different throughout the day!

Safety Notes
Adult supervision is recommended when using scissors. Keep contact paper away from very young children who may place it in their mouths.

Tissue Paper Suncatcher Video Script
